He said McCormick’s ‘cavalier 
disregard of the potentially fatal consequences’ of his racket convinced
him to pass the maximum sentence he could.

He added: ‘In terms of culpability and harm, I have been unable to imagine a more serious case of its kind.

‘The device was useless, the profits outrageous and your culpability as a fraudster has to be placed in the highest category.

‘I am wholly satisfied that your 
fraudulent conduct in selling so many useless devices for simply 
enormous profit promoted a false sense of security and in all 
probability materially contributed to causing death and injury to 
innocent individuals.’

